    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a good start for the intro. Some of my students might ask why we call it \"substantive\" instead of just \"due process\" though. Could you add a bit more detail to the explanation explaining why this specific type of due process is necessary for civil rights, compared to just following the standard legal procedures?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"substantive\" aspect is necessary because it looks *at the substance* of the law, not just its procedure. Standard due process only requires that the government follow fair rules when taking away a right, but substantive due process asks whether the right itself is fundamental enough to be protected. This allows courts to invalidate laws that might be procedurally fair but fundamentally violate deeply held liberties, like personal autonomy or privacy.",
      "source": "target",
